generated_text:
Alright, I need to draft a promotional email in HTML format for a reserved gift. The user wants it to include layout and design styles, so I should make sure it's visually appealing and well-structured.

First, I'll start with the basic HTML structure: doctype, html, head, and body tags. In the head, I'll include meta tags for charset and viewport to ensure proper rendering on different devices. The title should be something relevant, like "Reserved Gift Email."

Next, I'll add a style section within the head for CSS. I'll reset margins and paddings with a universal selector and set box-sizing to border-box for easier layout management. The font should be clean and readable, so I'll choose Arial as a safe option.

The header will have a background color to stand out. I'll use a gradient for a modern look, maybe purples and blues. The content should include the customer's name and the gift details, styled with a slightly lighter background and centered text.

For the body, I'll use a grid layout to make it responsive. On larger screens, it'll have two columns side by side, and on mobile, it'll stack into a single column. Each column will have a card layout with a background color and padding for a clean look.

Each card will highlight a different aspect of the gift: name, description, price, and a call-to-action button. The name and price should be prominent, so I'll use bold and larger fonts. The description will be in a smaller font and aligned to the left for readability.

The button needs to stand out, so I'll choose a contrasting color, maybe red, with white text. Adding a hover effect with a slight lift will make it interactive.

At the bottom, I'll include a footer with the company logo and copyright information. The logo should be simple, maybe a logo symbol within a circle, styled with a subtle background color.

I'll make sure the colors are consistent and the layout is responsive, using media queries if necessary. Testing the email in different browsers might be needed to ensure compatibility, but I'll keep it simple for now.

Finally, I'll review the HTML structure to ensure all elements are properly closed and the styles are correctly applied. The result should be a professional and attractive promotional email that effectively communicates the reserved gift offer.
</think>

